ce:section.ce:para:
Synthesis and structural analysis of Zn-MOF@COF: As can be seen in Scheme 1 , the COF has been prepared from synthesized Btc-NH-NH2 and terephthaldehyde in 1,4-dioxane at 120 °C for 12 h. The MOF has been prepared by using a solvothermal method from Zn nitrate and 2,6-naphthalene-dicarboxylic acid at 100 °C for 72 h. The successful synthesis of Zn-MOF was confirmed by single-crystal XRD analysis. The SCXRD results suggest that the Zn-MOF crystallizes in a monoclinic crystal system with space group C2/c. The Zn-centre adopt distorted square pyramidal geometry with one water molecule coordinated with the Zn-centre at the axial position and four O atoms of the linker at the equatorial position (Figure S15). The organic linker acts as a bridge between two Zn atoms and forms the 3D framework (
Figure S16
). Moreover, the framework of Zn-MOF was simplified by using ToposPro software to gain more insights into the structure. The Zn-MOF exhibit pts type topology with point symbol {42.8.4}. The framework of Zn-MOF can be viewed as a 2-nodal 4,4-connected net with (4-c)(4-c) stoichiometry (Figure S17). The crystallographic parameters and other details of Zn-MOF were provided in Table S3 in ESI. Then, the Zn-MOF@COF composite was synthesized solvothermally from COF, Zn nitrate and 2,6-naphthalene-dicarboxylic acid at 100 °C for 72 h. The resulting greyish solid was obtained after filtration and washing with DMF and methanol at least thrice. The Zn-MOF@COF is insoluble in common organic solvents and water, making it suitable as a chemical sensor for water pollutants. The surface morphology of Zn-MOF@COF, COF and Zn-MOF were examined by SEM analysis. Further, the Zn-MOF@COF were characterised by FTIR, PXRD, BET and XPS techniques.
